./.title: General
./.body:
Clicktale for Apps
Welcome to Clicktale for Apps SDK documentation.
In the menu to the left you can find integration guides and other resources on how to interact and use the SDK API for both Android and iOS. 
Please contact your dedicated Clicktale project manager or account manager for information on how to obtain the SDK itself or any other question which is not covered in the documentation found here.

general/data-types.html.title: Data Types
general/data-types.html.body:
Data Types
Clicktale for apps collects two main data types:

Session Playbacks
Meta-data

Session Playbacks
Clicktale records your user activity within the app and allows you to playback real user sessions.
The recorded session are accessible for three months (90 days). After this period the playback videos will be deleted.
Metadata
Clicktale for apps collects metadata which includes all other analytical functionality such as events, screen views, gestures and more.
Metadata is saved for over a year – this data is used to generate the different reports and deeper insights that you see inside the Clicktale for Apps platform.
The data retention value can be changed by request per application – please contact Clicktale to find out more information about changing the data retention duration.

general/performance.html.title: Performance
general/performance.html.body:
Performance
The Clicktale for Apps SDK is designed to run in the background and avoid causing any lags or delays to your application. Clicktale for Apps today is running on many large scale apps, generating billions of recordings per month transparently helping our enterprise customers deliver more revenue and better experiences.
Clicktale has been serving leading enterprises for over 10 years and is known as the pioneer in improving digital customer experiences. As such, we have put a lot of engineering effort into our SDK to ensure that when using Clicktale for Apps, the user experience will be improved – not hindered.
There are multiple mechanisms that control the behavior of the SDK in your application – all of them are fully configurable and controlled by the customer – you. 

Via remote configuration, you can turn the SDK on or off at any time.
You can also remotely target the SDK to only record on specific devices, OS, or for specific versions of your app. 

The benefit here is that you can change these settings without needing to release new versions of your application, as these are controlled by remote configuration.
Moreover, this SDK was designed to be compatible with even very old versions of smartphones such as iPhone 4 and iPhone 5 hardware or Android 2.0 and 4.0. Note that support for older versions of Android and iOS may be deprecated in the future (in regards of OS version and SDK level)
While testing different hardware configurations, we find that on the oldest type of devices such as iPhone 4/5, performance demands will be up to 20%. This means that on these old types of devices you will see a slightly higher battery consumption when the SDK is running. Nonetheless – there will be no lag or latency inside the application, i.e. users will not feel that anything is impacting their experience.
On more modern iOS devices such as the iPhone 6/7 or other 2015 devices and more recent, we see very low performance demands and no noticeable impact by users.
On modern Android devices, the main load of generating the playback of the session is done after the app is closed and terminated - making it also completely transparent during actual usage.

general/hybrid-applications.html.title: Hybrid Applications
general/hybrid-applications.html.body:
Hybrid Applications Support
Clicktale for Apps SDK supports recording and providing analytics for Hybrid Applications.
A hybrid application can either be based on a framework such as Cordova or an application which displays data from a WebView like object.
Because of the way our SDK captures data - the resulting session video will automatically capture and include data coming from hybrid content.
For more infomation about Cordova, please see the Cordova Integration instructions.
When it comes to hiding sensitive information or passing custom events from within the content coming from the web view, some customization may be required, please look at the description at the different Privacy pages for more information.

general/faq.html.title: FAQ
general/faq.html.body:
FAQ
Data and Performance
How will Clicktale SDK affect my App performance?
It will not. Please look at the Performance article for more information.
When is data sent by the SDK
We record data and process it on the device only after the user has left your app. We will then send this data back to the server.
Will the SDK use my users data plan
The video session data can be configured to be sent over WiFi only or cellular only, or both.
You are in control on how it behaves, and this configuration can be done remotly so no redployment of the app is required if you change your mind.
How much data is sent
The data transmitted depends on the quality of the recording – for the lowest quality the video will be around 100-300KB per minute.
For the higher quality, the video can get up to 1MB per minute.
It is important to understand that the video compression used can vary between different applications, depending on the actual content that displayed on the screen.
Where do I go to add Android or iOS app
When we define an 'app' inside our platform, it is both for Android/iOS. So when you initially log in and look at the dashboard view for your app, it will contain data from both iOS and Android.
Our platform knows how to segment the data correctly, both for heatmaps and any other segmentation that is done on the system.
Usually we create more than one project for your app, to segment data between development and production, but each one of these projects will hold data like any other from your entire app ecosystem. 
Privacy
When it comes to privacy, Clicktale offers several options to hide sensitive information from the recording, more details on how to implement the data hiding can be found at the respected plaform documents (Android / iOS)
Is it possible to hide sensitive fields from the recording
Yes, it is possible to completely block any UI element from the recording in both iOS and Android. More information can be found here for Android or iOS
Is data set as sensitive completely blocked or is masked at the Clicktale for Apps application / server
The data set as sensitive is completely blocked. This data is rendered as black areas on the client side and is never sent to Clicktale servers. 
What is private by default
By default, all sensitive fields (password fields) are automatically hidden from the recording.
The rest of the data is visible unless manual action is taken to block it – so if your application has sensitive data such as credit card information or any data that you would like to hide from the videos sent to Clicktale Servers – follow the articles around Privacy for any View to ensure the right data is blocked.
Additionally, the keyboard is not recorded, so when a keyboard is displayed on the screen, we will render part of the screen black where the keyboard was present.
Is the data collected by the SDK shared with any third party
No. The data collected by the SDK is sent to Clicktale servers and is never shared with an external source.
Is it possible to pause the recording / black out the entire screen
Yes it is, in the privacy articles (Android or iOS) there are APIs around the different controls you have around recording. It is possible to hide the entire screen with a single api or pause the recording completely.
How do I properly record login screens provided by SDKs such as Google login
Login SDKs usually show a WebView in order to provide functionality, Clicktale for Apps cannot ‘see’ what is happening inside that web view and thus cannot automatically hide the password fields showing in these screens. It is strongly recommended to set these views to private to avoid recording your customers private information.

ios/getting-started.html.title: Getting Started
ios/getting-started.html.body:
Getting Started with iOS
Adding the Framework to your project
The SDK is available via CocoaPods. If your project supports CocoaPods, you can add the following line to your Pod file:
pod ...
pod 'Clicktale'
pod ...
The Clicktale pod will add the framework.
Manual Integration
In order to add the framework manually, follow the next steps:

You will need obtain the Clicktale.framework 

You can find it at: https://github.com/Clicktale/ios-sdk/raw/master/Clicktale.zip




Add the Clicktale.framework to your project

Open your project settings > General > Embedded Binaries and add the Clicktale.framework

Import Clicktale.h file to access public methods of the framework.
 #import 

If working with Swift, please read the Swift integration guide.


Authentication
In order to ensure that only you can send data to your project, you are required to send your access key and secret key to authenticate with our server before you begin recording.
At the end of your  - application:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions: function, just before returning, add the following code:
- (BOOL)application:(UIApplication *)application didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:(NSDictionary *)launchOptions {
    //your code 

    [[Clicktale sharedInstance] setAccessKey:@"YOUR_ACCESS_KEY" secretKey:@"YOUR_SECRET_KEY"]; 
    [[Clicktale sharedInstance] startClicktale]; 

    return YES;
}

Or with Swift:
func application(application: UIApplication, didFinishLaunchingWithOptions launchOptions: [NSObject: AnyObject]?) -> Bool { 
    // Override point for customization after application launch. 

    Clicktale.sharedInstance().setAccessKey("YOUR_ACCESS_KEY, secretKey: "YOUR_SECRET_KEY") 
    Clicktale.sharedInstance().start() 
    return true
}

Start Recording
After you are authenticated, you will need to call the -startClicktale: method to begin the actual recording.
By default, the recording is stopped and uploaded to Clicktale server when session ends and the app is minimized to the background.
[[Clicktale sharedInstance] startClicktale];

Clicktale.sharedInstance().start()

This method creates a new session and starts recording the session. All the sensor & device information starts to be uploaded after startClicktale is called.

If you don’t use “Storyboards” in your Xcode project, you must call Clicktale methods after UIWindow created.
... 
[window addSubView:myViewController]; 
[[Clicktale sharedInstance] startClicktale]; 
...

ios/swift-integration.html.title: Swift Integration
ios/swift-integration.html.body:
Swift Integration
Clicktale for Apps is compatible with Apple’s new programming language Swift. Follow these steps for creating a new project

Create a project with Xcode
Select “Swift” as programming language
Create a file ( Header file .h ) and add it to your project( for example : YourProjectName-Bridging-Header.h )
Copy and paste the code below to YourProjectName-Bridging-Header.h

#import 


Modify Xcode project “Build Settings -> Objective-C Bridging Header” and set it to “YourProjectName\YourProjectName-Bridging-Header.h” as a path.
Add the SDK to your your project. It is the same SDK for Objective-C and Swift.

Initialize Clicktale for Apps in AppDelegate.swift



import Clicktale


func application(application: UIApplication, didFinishLaunchingWithOptions launchOptions: [NSObject: AnyObject]?) -> Bool { 

    // Override point for customization after application launch. 
    Clicktale.sharedInstance().setAccessKey("YOUR_ACCESS_KEY", secretKey: "YOUR_SECRET_KEY") 
    Clicktale.sharedInstance().start() 
    return true 
}

ios/using-events.html.title: Using Events
ios/using-events.html.body:
Using Events with iOS
Clicktale for Apps SDK enables you to send events to track various business states in your application. Events are later used to segment and analyze your data.
Setting the UserID
The UserID is an event you can use to help you understand and match which user as you know it has experienced what you see in the video recording.

You should use this method when the User identity is updated, either login / logout or at other steps where the unique ID of a user is set.

It is suggested to use UserID in order to allow you to track the same user across platforms or between server and client side events.
Example:
[[Clicktale sharedInstance] setSessionUserID:@"100"];

Or with Swift:
Clicktale.sharedInstance().setSessionUserID("100")

Parameters:
UserID: The applications-specific user identifier. Can be any alphanumeric value.
Tracking Events
Events are all the actions that occur in your app, and you want to measure. Each action has one or more related metrics that are incremented every time the event occurs.
For example, you can track events every time an item added to cart; a category selected, or an error message appeared.
Example:
Tracking an event without a value:
[[Clicktale sharedInstance] trackEvent:@"event_name"];

Or with Swift:
Clicktale.sharedInstance().trackEvent("event_name");

Tracking an event with a Value:
[[Clicktale sharedInstance] trackEvent:@"Search" value:"value"];

Or with Swift:
Clicktale.sharedInstance().trackEvent("event_name", value: "value");

Parameters:
event_name : The name of the event (e.g. "AddToCart")
value: A value is a specific data point for an event (e.g. "$3.72", "apple")
Tracking Page Views
Every time a new screen is displayed in your application (for example, when a user navigates from the home page to the news feed), it is being tracked automatically by the SDK. The automatic tracking follows ViewControllers loading and will write a page view automatically at that time.
In some cases, when the automatic detection is not good enough as the screen logical state changes without loading a new ViewController, or your app structure does not fit such detection and you choose to deactivate it, you can always track page views manually using the following API call.
Example:
[[Clicktale sharedInstance] trackPageView:@"ScreenName"];

Or with Swift:
Clicktale.sharedInstance().trackPageView("ScreenName");

Parameters:
ScreenName: The name of the screen (e.g. "Product Screen").
Tracking Web Events
We provide an API that enables applications that contain web pages (WKWebView only) to track events from them.
1.On the web page you can use this three JavaScript API's:
 //Tracking an event without a value:
 Clicktale.TrackEvent('event name here');

 //Tracking an event with a Value
 Clicktale.TrackEventAndValue('event name here','event value here');

 //Tracking a page view
 Clicktale.TrackPageView('page name here');

2.On the application side you need to bind your webView (WKWebView only), using this API:
[[Clicktale sharedInstance] bindWebViewForEventTracking:self.webView];

Or with Swift:
Clicktale.sharedInstance().bindWebView(forEventTracking: self.webView)

ios/advanced-features.html.title: Advanced Features
ios/advanced-features.html.body:
Advanced Features
Controlling Crash Reporting
In some cases there is already an existing crash reporting solution and Clicktale's may conflict with it - to enable the ability to have both solutions you can disable Clicktale's crash reporting functions.
When disabled, the recording will still work, and any data integration which enables you to see the Clicktale session link from the existing crash reporting solution will still work as expected.
To disable crash reporting on iOS:
-(void)setCrashReporterOff;

Or with Swift:
open func setCrashReporterOff()

Call that function before called startClicktale if you do not want the SDK to collect crash information.
Debug Mode
When developing, in order to get immediate feedback on how the SDK captures data, specifically how the video look, you can activate debug mode. We find this being used the most when testing is PII is hidden correctly.
When active, this will cause the videos to be saved to the Photos Album on the device, before they are uploaded to our server.
In order to activate debug mode, use the following function:
-(void)setDebugMode:(BOOL)on;

Or with Swift:
open func setDebugMode(_ on: Bool)

Calling it with true will activate it, false will deactivate it.
This will require access permission to the camera roll - if that permission is not required for your application it is recommended to remove it after the development cycle is complete 
Session Location
Clicktale for Apps enables you to see the location of where the session was recorded at, in case your application uses location services and collects the user location, you can can send the location to the SDK and it will be displayed in the dashboard.
Use the following API to track location:
-(void)trackGeoLocation:(CLLocation *)location;

Or with Swift:
open func trackGeoLocation(_ location: CLLocation!)

Improving data delivery
Clicktale recommends sending the video data over WiFi to avoid any data charges for your users. Depending on your app usage, there may be scenarios where it will not be used in WiFi which means the amount of videos you will be able to capture will be much lower than actual recordings.
In order to improve data and video delivery to Clicktale you can use the Background Fetch mechanism, the apple documentation on that API can be found here. 
If you are already using background execution, add a call to the following function provided by the Clicktale SDK, this should be placed in the performFetchWithCompletionHandler which should already present in the AppDelegate file
-(void)flushDataInBackgroundWithCompletionHandler:(void (^)(UIBackgroundFetchResult result))completionHandler;

Or with Swift:
open func flushDataInBackground(completionHandler: ((UIBackgroundFetchResult) -> Swift.Void)!)

Paramater: completionHandler 
If you use the background fetch for just Clicktale, you can pass the completionHandler - the Background Fetch completionHandler you recived from performFetchWithCompletionHandler, and upon data transfer complete by Clicktale, we will call the complition handler for you.
If you use background fetch for additional updates pass nil completionHandler. In this case, upon data transfer complete we will post a notification:  kCTClicktaleBackgroundDataFlushFinish.
At that point you should call the completionHandler yourself, the Clicktale code will not do it.
A full use of the mechanism can be found in our demo app.
Implementing Background Execution
If you are not using Background Execution yet, you will need to add the performFetchWithCompletionHandler function to your AppDelegate:
-(void)application:(UIApplication *)application performFetchWithCompletionHandler:(void (^)(UIBackgroundFetchResult result))completionHandler;

Or with Swift:
optional func application(_ application: UIApplication, performFetchWithCompletionHandler completionHandler: @escaping (UIBackgroundFetchResult) -> Void)

Part of enabling background execution will require you to also enable the background fetching via adding the following to your didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:
[[UIApplication sharedApplication] setMinimumBackgroundFetchInterval:UIApplicationBackgroundFetchIntervalMinimum];

Or with Swift:
 UIApplication.shared.setMinimumBackgroundFetchInterval(UIApplicationBackgroundFetchIntervalMinimum)

This call to setMinimumBackgroundFetchInterval need to be performed from the AppDelegate at:
-(BOOL)application:(UIApplication *)application didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:(NSDictionary *)launchOptions;

Or with Swift:
func application(_ application: UIApplication, didFinishLaunchingWithOptions launchOptions: [UIApplicationLaunchOptionsKey: Any]?) -> Bool

Finally, you need to enable (check the box) Background fetch in the Capabilities tab of your application.
The full description of the implementation can be found at the Apple documentation for background execution. 
Using Push Notifications to Improve Data Delivery
In addition to the above article, you can improve data delivery by utilising the Silent Push Notification mechanism.
The full description of the implementation can be found at the Apple documentation for Using Push Notifications to Initiate a Download. 
You can call this method:
-(void)flushDataInBackgroundWithCompletionHandler:(void (^)(UIBackgroundFetchResult result))completionHandler;

Or with Swift:
open func flushDataInBackground(completionHandler: ((UIBackgroundFetchResult) -> Swift.Void)!)

From the AppDelegate method as such:
- (void)application:(UIApplication *)application didReceiveRemoteNotification:(NSDictionary *)userInfo fetchCompletionHandler:(void (^)(UIBackgroundFetchResult result))completionHandler
{
 //Support for silent push notification
 [[Clicktale sharedInstance] flushDataInBackgroundWithCompletionHandler: completionHandler];
}

Or with Swift:
 func application(_ application: UIApplication, didReceiveRemoteNotification userInfo: [AnyHashable : Any], fetchCompletionHandler completionHandler: @escaping (UIBackgroundFetchResult) -> Void) {
  //Support for silent push notification
  Clicktale.sharedInstance().flushDataInBackground(completionHandler: completionHandler)
 }

Paramater: completionHandler 
If you use the Silent Push Notification for just Clicktale, you can pass the completionHandler - the Fetch completionHandler you recived from didReceiveRemoteNotification, and upon data transfer complete by Clicktale, we will call the complition handler for you.
If you use Silent Push Notification for additional updates pass nil completionHandler. In this case, upon data transfer complete we will post a notification:  kCTClicktaleBackgroundDataFlushFinish.
At that point you should call the completionHandler yourself, the Clicktale code will not do it.

heatmaps/setting-up-heatmaps.html.title: Setting up Heatmaps
heatmaps/setting-up-heatmaps.html.body:
Setting up Heatmaps
In Clicktale for Apps, heatmap functionality comes out of the box as the SDK will capture all the taps and other gestures that your users are performing in the application.
We later take that data, and group it according to ‘Screens’ or ‘Page Views’. This is done to logically capture the correct data per screen, or data layer that you display in your application, so for example:

The application starts with a ‘Home Page’, showing some highlights of your products.
A user clicks on a Menu, the menu layer appears on the screen
A user then either clicks on some item to view the next screen, or goes back to the ‘Home Page’

So the ‘Home Page’ screen was displayed, and interactions happened on it, and then later a Menu screen, or layer was displayed.
We can show you the interactions aggregated only for the ‘Home Page’ and then only for the menu layer – keep your analysis accurate and conclusions to the point.
All that is required is signaling to the SDK which logical screen is currently showing – through the API. More information on how to do so is available at the using events article of the specific platform you are working on: iOS or Android.
Out of the box, we monitor ViewController initializations on iOS and Activities on Android and send an automatic Screen View event as usually these would signify a logical change in the application. This behavior can be controlled via configuration and be turned off if it does not match the logic of your app.
For more complex applications, it is important to remember to fire the Screen/Page View event not only at the creation of the current view, but also when transitioning.
So in the example above, after the user looked at the menu layer, if he then went back to the 'Home Page', you need to fire that event again so the SDK knows the menu visuals are not longer displayed, and the taps collected right now are relevant for the home screen again.

heatmaps/using-heatmaps.html.title: Using Heatmaps
heatmaps/using-heatmaps.html.body:
Using Heatmaps
After you finish setting up your application for heat-maps, to access the heat map, navigate to the heat maps area of Clicktale for Apps.
Segmentation of heatmaps is a little different than the rest of the product. They are always segmented by the platform, ‘Page View’ and the application version – before applying any other segmentation filters familiar from the session playback or other features available in Clicktale for Apps.
We segment according to Page View because taps data is only relevant to the page displayed right now. This logical page or screen is may differ from one version to another as the UX or design may change and of course, things may not look the same between different platforms.
These reasons are why the segmentation is done first by the Platform, Page and Version, and only then the rest of the segmentation filters are applied such as events, users and so on.
The heat map displayed is using only the tap data and can be referred to as a tap heat map, no swipes or pinch gestures are included in the heat map.
